Subject Content
3.1 Biological Molecules
3.1.1 Monomers and Polymers
Monomers are smaller units from which larger molecules are made
Polymers are molecules made from a large number of monomers joined together
Monosaccharides, amino acids and nucleotides are examples of monomers
A condensation reaction joins two molecules together with formation of a chemical bond and involves elimination of a molecule of water
A hydrolysis reaction breaks a chemical bond between two molecules and involves use of a water molecule
3.1.2 Carbohydrates
Monosaccharides are the monomers from which larger carbohydrates are made. Glucose, galactose and fructose are common monosaccharides
A condensation reaction between two monosaccharides forms a glycosidic bond
Disaccharides are formed by condensation of two monosaccharides:
Maltose = glucose + glucose
Sucrose = glucose + fructose
Lactose = glucose + galactose
Glucose has two isomers: α-glucose and β-glucose
Polysaccharides are formed by condensation of many glucose units:
Glycogen and starch are formed from α-glucose
Cellulose is formed from β-glucose
The basic structure and functions of glycogen, starch and cellulose; relationship of structure to function in animal and plant cells
Biochemical tests: Benedict's solution for reducing/non-reducing sugars; iodine/potassium iodide for starch
3.1.3 Lipids
Triglycerides are formed by condensation of one glycerol + three fatty acids
A condensation reaction between glycerol and a fatty acid forms an ester bond
The R-group of a fatty acid may be saturated or unsaturated
In phospholipids, one fatty acid is substituted by a phosphate-containing group
Different properties of triglycerides and phospholipids related to their structures
Emulsion test for lipids
Students should recognise saturated/unsaturated fatty acids from diagrams and explain different properties
3.1.4 Proteins
3.1.4.1 General Properties of Proteins
Amino acids are monomers of proteins
General structure: NH₂–C(R)–COOH (amine group, carboxyl group, R side chain)
20 common amino acids differ only in their side group
Condensation of two amino acids forms a peptide bond
Dipeptides = two amino acids
Polypeptides = many amino acids
A functional protein may contain one or more polypeptides
Role of hydrogen bonds, ionic bonds and disulfide bridges in protein structure
Relationship between primary, secondary, tertiary and quaternary structure and protein function
Biuret test for proteins
3.1.4.2 Many Proteins Are Enzymes
Each enzyme lowers the activation energy of the reaction it catalyses
Induced-fit model of enzyme action
Enzyme specificity relates to tertiary structure of active site and complementary substrate(s) → enzyme-substrate complex
Effects on rate of enzyme-controlled reactions:
Enzyme concentration
Substrate concentration
Competitive and non-competitive inhibitors
pH and temperature
Required Practical 1: Investigation into the effect of a named variable on the rate of an enzyme-controlled reaction.

3.1.5 Nucleic Acids
3.1.5.1 Structure of DNA and RNA
DNA and RNA are polymers of nucleotides
Each nucleotide = pentose sugar + nitrogen-containing organic base + phosphate group
DNA nucleotide: deoxyribose + phosphate + adenine/cytosine/guanine/thymine
RNA nucleotide: ribose + phosphate + adenine/cytosine/guanine/uracil
Condensation between two nucleotides forms a phosphodiester bond
DNA = double helix, two polynucleotide chains held by hydrogen bonds between complementary base pairs
RNA = relatively short single polynucleotide chain
3.1.5.2 DNA Replication
Semi-conservative replication ensures genetic continuity
Process:
Unwinding of the double helix
Breakage of hydrogen bonds between complementary bases
DNA helicase unwinds DNA and breaks hydrogen bonds
New DNA nucleotides attracted to exposed bases on template strands; base pairing
DNA polymerase catalyses condensation joining adjacent nucleotides
3.1.6 ATP
ATP = ribose + adenine + three phosphate groups (nucleotide derivative)
Hydrolysis of ATP → ADP + Pi, catalysed by ATP hydrolase
Coupled to energy-requiring reactions in cells
Released Pi can phosphorylate other compounds, making them more reactive
ATP resynthesised by condensation of ADP + Pi, catalysed by ATP synthase (during photosynthesis or respiration)
3.1.7 Water
Important properties of water in biology:

Metabolite in condensation and hydrolysis reactions
Important solvent for metabolic reactions
Relatively high heat capacity — buffers temperature changes
Relatively large latent heat of vaporisation — cooling effect with little water loss
Strong cohesion between molecules — supports water columns in plants; produces surface tension
3.1.8 Inorganic Ions
Occur in solution in cytoplasm and body fluids (some at high, some at very low concentrations)
Specific roles: hydrogen ions and pH; iron ions in haemoglobin; sodium ions in co-transport of glucose/amino acids; phosphate ions in DNA and ATP
3.2 Cells
3.2.1 Cell Structure
3.2.1.1 Structure of Eukaryotic Cells
Structure and function of:

Cell-surface membrane
Nucleus (chromosomes = protein-bound linear DNA; nucleoli)
Mitochondria
Chloroplasts (plants and algae)
Golgi apparatus and Golgi vesicles
Lysosomes (membrane-bound; release hydrolytic enzymes)
Ribosomes
Rough endoplasmic reticulum and smooth endoplasmic reticulum
Cell wall (plants, algae, fungi)
Cell vacuole (plants)
In complex multicellular organisms: specialised cells → tissues → organs → systems.

3.2.1.2 Structure of Prokaryotic Cells and Viruses
Prokaryotic cells differ from eukaryotic cells:

Cytoplasm lacks membrane-bound organelles
Smaller ribosomes
No nucleus; single circular DNA molecule, free in cytoplasm, not associated with proteins
Cell wall containing murein (a glycoprotein)
Many also have: plasmids, capsule, flagella
Viruses are acellular and non-living. Structure: genetic material, capsid, attachment protein.

3.2.1.3 Methods of Studying Cells
Principles and limitations of optical microscopes, TEM and SEM
Measuring size of objects with optical microscope
Difference between magnification and resolution
Formula: magnification = size of image ÷ size of real object
Principles of cell fractionation and ultracentrifugation
3.2.2 All Cells Arise from Other Cells
Not all cells retain ability to divide
Cell cycle: DNA replication during interphase; mitosis produces two identical daughter cells
Behaviour of chromosomes during: interphase, prophase, metaphase, anaphase, telophase
Role of spindle fibres attached to centromeres in separating chromatids
Cytokinesis — division of cytoplasm
Mitosis is controlled; uncontrolled division → tumours/cancers
Binary fission in prokaryotes: replication of circular DNA and plasmids; cytoplasm division
Viruses: non-living, do not divide; infected host cell replicates virus particles
Required Practical 2: Preparation of stained squashes of cells from plant root tips; use of optical microscope to identify stages of mitosis; calculation of mitotic index.

3.2.3 Transport Across Cell Membranes
Fluid-mosaic model: phospholipids, proteins, glycoproteins, glycolipids; cholesterol restricts movement
Movement across membranes:
Simple diffusion (limitations of phospholipid bilayer)
Facilitated diffusion (carrier proteins, channel proteins)
Osmosis (in terms of water potential)
Active transport (carrier proteins; hydrolysis of ATP)
Co-transport (absorption of Na⁺ and glucose in mammalian ileum)
Adaptations for rapid transport: increased surface area; increased number of protein channels/carriers
Required Practical 3: Production of a dilution series of a solute to produce a calibration curve to identify water potential of plant tissue.

Required Practical 4: Investigation into the effect of a named variable on the permeability of cell-surface membranes.

3.2.4 Cell Recognition and the Immune System
Cell-surface molecules identify cells (proteins); immune system identifies pathogens, foreign cells, abnormal cells, toxins
Antigen definition; effect of antigen variability on disease/prevention
Phagocytosis of pathogens; destruction by lysozymes
T lymphocyte response (cellular response):
Antigen-presenting cells
Helper T cells (TH) stimulate cytotoxic T cells (TC), B cells, phagocytes
B lymphocyte response (humoral response):
Antibody definition and structure
Antigen-antibody complex → agglutination and phagocytosis
Plasma cells and memory cells → primary and secondary immune responses
Vaccines: protection for individuals and populations; herd immunity
Active vs passive immunity
HIV structure and replication in helper T cells; how HIV causes AIDS; why antibiotics are ineffective against viruses
Monoclonal antibodies: targeting medication, medical diagnosis, ELISA test
Ethical issues with vaccines and monoclonal antibodies
3.3 Organisms Exchange Substances with Their Environment
3.3.1 Surface Area to Volume Ratio
Relationship between organism size and SA:V ratio
Changes to body shape and development of systems as adaptations when ratio reduces
Relationship between SA:V ratio and metabolic rate
3.3.2 Gas Exchange
Adaptations of gas exchange surfaces:

Across body surface of single-celled organisms
Tracheal system of insects (tracheae, tracheoles, spiracles)
Gills of fish (gill lamellae, filaments, counter-current principle)
Leaves of dicotyledonous plants (mesophyll, stomata)
Structural/functional compromises between gas exchange efficiency and water loss limitation (insects, xerophytic plants)
Human gas exchange system:

Alveoli, bronchioles, bronchi, trachea, lungs
Alveolar epithelium as exchange surface
Ventilation mechanism: diaphragm, external/internal intercostal muscles, pressure changes in thoracic cavity
3.3.3 Digestion and Absorption
Large biological molecules hydrolysed to smaller molecules for absorption
Carbohydrate digestion: amylases, membrane-bound disaccharidases
Lipid digestion: lipase + bile salts
Protein digestion: endopeptidases, exopeptidases, membrane-bound dipeptidases
Absorption mechanisms:
Co-transport for amino acids and monosaccharides
Role of micelles in lipid absorption
3.3.4 Mass Transport
3.3.4.1 Mass Transport in Animals
Haemoglobin: quaternary structure protein; role in O₂ transport
Oxyhaemoglobin dissociation curve; loading, transport, unloading of O₂
Cooperative binding: first O₂ binding changes shape, making further binding easier
Bohr effect: CO₂ concentration affects O₂ dissociation
Different haemoglobin types in different animals
Mammalian blood circulation; coronary arteries; vessels entering/leaving heart, lungs, kidneys
Heart structure: pressure/volume changes during cardiac cycle; valve movements; unidirectional flow
Arteries, arterioles, veins — structure related to function
Capillaries and capillary beds as exchange surfaces; tissue fluid formation and return
Required Practical 5: Dissection of animal or plant gas exchange system or mass transport system.

3.3.4.2 Mass Transport in Plants
Xylem: transports water; cohesion-tension theory
Phloem: transports organic substances; mass flow hypothesis for translocation
Use of tracers and ringing experiments
3.4 Genetic Information, Variation and Relationships Between Organisms
3.4.1 DNA, Genes and Chromosomes
Prokaryotic DNA: short, circular, not associated with proteins
Eukaryotic nuclear DNA: very long, linear, associated with histones → chromosome
Mitochondrial/chloroplast DNA: short, circular, not associated with protein
Gene: base sequence of DNA coding for amino acid sequence of a polypeptide OR a functional RNA (rRNA, tRNA)
Gene occupies a fixed position (locus) on a particular DNA molecule
Triplet code: three DNA bases code for one amino acid; genetic code is universal, non-overlapping, degenerate
Much eukaryotic nuclear DNA is non-coding (e.g. non-coding multiple repeats between genes)
Within genes: exons (coding) separated by introns (non-coding)
3.4.2 DNA and Protein Synthesis
Genome: complete set of genes in a cell; Proteome: full range of proteins a cell can produce
Structure of mRNA and tRNA
Transcription: production of mRNA from DNA; role of RNA polymerase
Prokaryotes: transcription → mRNA directly
Eukaryotes: transcription → pre-mRNA → splicing → mRNA
Translation: production of polypeptides from mRNA codons; roles of ribosomes, tRNA, ATP
3.4.3 Genetic Diversity Can Arise as a Result of Mutation or During Meiosis
Gene mutations: change in base sequence; arise spontaneously during DNA replication
Base deletion and base substitution
Degenerate code means not all substitutions change amino acid sequence
Mutagenic agents increase mutation rate
Chromosome mutations: non-disjunction during meiosis
Meiosis produces genetically different daughter cells:
Two nuclear divisions → four haploid cells from one diploid cell
Independent segregation of homologous chromosomes
Crossing over between homologous chromosomes
Random fertilisation further increases genetic variation
3.4.4 Genetic Diversity and Adaptation
Genetic diversity: number of different alleles of genes in a population
Principles of natural selection:
Random mutation → new alleles
Advantageous alleles → increased reproductive success
Inherited by next generation → increased frequency over generations
Directional selection (e.g. antibiotic resistance in bacteria)
Stabilising selection (e.g. human birth weights)
Adaptations: anatomical, physiological, behavioural
Required Practical 6: Use of aseptic techniques to investigate the effect of antimicrobial substances on microbial growth.

3.4.5 Species and Taxonomy
Species: organisms that produce fertile offspring
Courtship behaviour: species recognition
Phylogenetic classification: hierarchy based on evolutionary relationships
Taxa: domain, kingdom, phylum, class, order, family, genus, species
Binomial nomenclature (e.g. Homo sapiens)
3.4.6 Biodiversity Within a Community
Species richness: number of different species in a community
Index of diversity: relationship between number of species and individuals per species
Formula: d = N(N−1) / Σn(n−1)
N = total organisms of all species; n = total organisms of each species
Farming techniques reduce biodiversity; balance between conservation and farming
3.4.7 Investigating Diversity
Genetic diversity can be compared by:

Frequency of measurable/observable characteristics
Base sequence of DNA or mRNA
Amino acid sequence of proteins
Quantitative investigations of variation:

Collecting data from random samples
Calculating mean and standard deviation
Interpreting mean values and standard deviations
3.5 Energy Transfers in and Between Organisms (A-Level Only)
3.5.1 Photosynthesis
Light-dependent reaction:

Chlorophyll absorbs light → photoionisation
Energy from electrons conserved in production of ATP and reduced NADP
ATP production: electron transfer chain → protons across chloroplast membranes → ATP synthase (chemiosmotic theory)
Photolysis of water → protons + electrons + oxygen
Light-independent reaction (Calvin cycle):

CO₂ + RuBP → 2× GP (catalysed by rubisco)
ATP + reduced NADP reduce GP → triose phosphate
Some TP regenerates RuBP
Some TP converted to useful organic substances
Required Practical 7: Use of chromatography to investigate pigments isolated from leaves of different plants.

Required Practical 8: Investigation into the effect of a named factor on the rate of dehydrogenase activity in extracts of chloroplasts.

3.5.2 Respiration
Glycolysis (cytoplasm, anaerobic):

Phosphorylation of glucose → glucose phosphate (using ATP)
Production of triose phosphate
Oxidation of triose phosphate → pyruvate + net gain of ATP + reduced NAD
Anaerobic only: pyruvate → ethanol or lactate (using reduced NAD; regenerates NAD)

Aerobic respiration (pyruvate enters mitochondrial matrix by active transport):

Pyruvate oxidised to acetate (reduced NAD produced)
Acetate + coenzyme A → acetyl CoA (link reaction)
Acetyl CoA + four-carbon molecule → six-carbon molecule → Krebs cycle
Krebs cycle: oxidation-reduction reactions → reduced coenzymes + ATP (substrate-level phosphorylation) + CO₂
Oxidative phosphorylation: electron transfer chain → protons across inner mitochondrial membranes → ATP synthase (chemiosmotic theory)
Other respiratory substrates: breakdown products of lipids and amino acids enter Krebs cycle
Required Practical 9: Investigation into the effect of a named variable on the rate of respiration of cultures of single-celled organisms.

3.5.3 Energy and Ecosystems
GPP (gross primary production) = chemical energy store in plant biomass
NPP (net primary production) = GPP − R (respiratory losses)
NPP available for plant growth/reproduction and other trophic levels
Net production of consumers: N = I − (F + R)
I = ingested food energy; F = faeces/urine energy loss; R = respiratory losses
Productivity = biomass in a given area in a given time (e.g. kJ ha⁻¹ year⁻¹)
Farming practices increase efficiency: simplifying food webs; reducing respiratory losses
3.5.4 Nutrient Cycles
Nutrients recycled within ecosystems (nitrogen cycle, phosphorus cycle)
Role of saprobionts in decomposition
Role of mycorrhizae in facilitating uptake of water and inorganic ions
Bacteria in nitrogen cycle: saprobiotic nutrition, ammonification, nitrification, nitrogen fixation, denitrification
Natural and artificial fertilisers replace nitrates/phosphates
Environmental issues: leaching and eutrophication
3.6 Organisms Respond to Changes in Their Internal and External Environments (A-Level Only)
3.6.1 Stimuli, Response and Receptors
3.6.1.1 Survival and Response
Organisms respond to environmental changes to increase survival
Plant growth factors: IAA (indoleacetic acid) effects on cell elongation in roots/shoots → gravitropism, phototropism
Taxes and kineses as simple responses
Simple reflex: three-neurone reflex arc (protective effect)
Required Practical 10: Investigation into the effect of an environmental variable on the movement of an animal using a choice chamber or maze.

3.6.1.2 Receptors
Pacinian corpuscle: responds to specific stimuli; deformation of stretch-mediated Na⁺ channels → generator potential
Human retina: rods (sensitivity to light) and cones (colour vision, visual acuity); connections to optic nerve
3.6.1.3 Control of Heart Rate
Myogenic stimulation; wave of electrical activity
SAN (sinoatrial node), AVN (atrioventricular node), Purkyne tissue in bundle of His
Chemoreceptors, pressure receptors, autonomic nervous system
Cardiac output: CO = stroke volume × heart rate
3.6.2 Nervous Coordination
3.6.2.1 Nerve Impulses
Structure of myelinated motor neurone
Resting potential: differential membrane permeability, electrochemical gradients, Na⁺/K⁺ movement
Depolarisation and action potential generation; all-or-nothing principle
Passage of action potential along non-myelinated and myelinated axons
Refractory period: discrete impulses, limits frequency
Speed factors: myelination (saltatory conduction), axon diameter, temperature
3.6.2.2 Synaptic Transmission
Structure of synapse and neuromuscular junction
Cholinergic synapse transmission: unidirectionality, temporal/spatial summation, inhibition
Comparison of cholinergic synapse and neuromuscular junction
3.6.3 Skeletal Muscles
Antagonistic pairs against incompressible skeleton
Gross and microscopic structure of skeletal muscle; ultrastructure of myofibril
Roles of actin, myosin, calcium ions, ATP in contraction
Calcium ions and tropomyosin in actinomyosin bridge formation cycle
ATP and phosphocreatine in muscle contraction
Slow and fast skeletal muscle fibres: structure, location, properties
3.6.4 Homeostasis
3.6.4.1 Principles of Homeostasis and Negative Feedback
Maintaining stable: core temperature, blood pH (enzyme activity), blood glucose (respiratory substrate, water potential)
Negative feedback restores systems to original level
Separate mechanisms for departures in different directions → greater control
3.6.4.2 Control of Blood Glucose Concentration
Factors influencing blood glucose concentration
Liver: glycogenesis, glycogenolysis, gluconeogenesis
Insulin: receptors on target cells → glucose uptake (channel proteins in membranes) → glucose → glycogen
Glucagon: receptors → glycogen → glucose; glycerol/amino acids → glucose
Adrenaline: receptors → glycogen → glucose
Second messenger model: adenylate cyclase → cAMP → protein kinase
Type I and Type II diabetes; control by insulin/diet
Required Practical 11: Production of a dilution series of glucose solution; use of colorimetric techniques to produce a calibration curve to identify glucose concentration in an unknown 'urine' sample.

3.6.4.3 Control of Blood Water Potential
Osmoregulation: control of blood water potential
Roles of hypothalamus, posterior pituitary, ADH
Nephron: glomerular filtrate formation; glucose/water reabsorption (PCT); Na⁺ gradient in medulla (loop of Henle); water reabsorption (DCT, collecting ducts)
3.7 Genetics, Populations, Evolution and Ecosystems (A-Level Only)
3.7.1 Inheritance
Genotype = genetic constitution; phenotype = expression + environment
Alleles: dominant, recessive, codominant
Homozygous or heterozygous at a specific locus
Genetic diagrams for:
Monohybrid and dihybrid crosses (dominant, recessive, codominant alleles)
Sex-linkage, autosomal linkage, multiple alleles, epistasis
Chi-squared (χ²) test: goodness of fit of observed vs expected phenotypic ratios
3.7.2 Populations
Population: group of same species, same place, same time, can potentially interbreed
Gene pool and allele frequency
Hardy-Weinberg principle: allele frequencies unchanged generation to generation (under specific conditions)
Hardy-Weinberg equation: p² + 2pq + q² = 1
p = frequency of dominant allele; q = frequency of recessive allele
3.7.3 Evolution May Lead to Speciation
Variation in phenotype: genetic and environmental factors; primary source = mutation
Meiosis and random fertilisation → further genetic variation
Natural selection: differential survival and reproduction
Effects of stabilising, directional and disruptive selection
Evolution = change in allele frequencies in a population
Reproductive isolation → accumulation of genetic differences → new species
Allopatric and sympatric speciation
Genetic drift: important in small populations
3.7.4 Populations in Ecosystems
Community + non-living components = ecosystem
Niche: governed by adaptation to abiotic and biotic conditions
Carrying capacity; affected by abiotic factors, interspecific/intraspecific competition, predation
Population estimation:
Quadrats (random or belt transect) for non-motile organisms
Mark-release-recapture for motile organisms (and its assumptions)
Primary succession: colonisation by pioneer species → climax community
Each stage changes environment → more suitable for other species
Conservation involves management of succession
Required Practical 12: Investigation into the effect of a named environmental factor on the distribution of a given species.

3.8 The Control of Gene Expression (A-Level Only)
3.8.1 Alteration of the Sequence of Bases in DNA
Gene mutations during DNA replication: addition, deletion, substitution, inversion, duplication, translocation
Mutations occur spontaneously; rate increased by mutagenic agents
Some mutations change only one triplet (degenerate code → may not change amino acid)
Some mutations cause a frame shift (change all downstream triplets)
3.8.2 Gene Expression Is Controlled by a Number of Features
3.8.2.1 Most of a Cell's DNA Is Not Translated
Totipotent cells: can produce any type of body cell (limited time in early embryos)
Pluripotent stem cells: divide in unlimited numbers; used in treating disorders
Multipotent and unipotent cells in mature mammals (e.g. cardiomyocytes)
Induced pluripotent stem cells (iPS cells): produced from adult somatic cells using protein transcription factors
3.8.2.2 Regulation of Transcription and Translation
Specific transcription factors move from cytoplasm to nucleus to stimulate/inhibit target genes
Role of oestrogen in initiating transcription
Epigenetic control: heritable changes in gene function without changes to base sequence
Increased methylation of DNA → inhibits transcription
Decreased acetylation of histones → inhibits transcription
Relevance to disease development/treatment (especially cancer)
RNA interference (RNAi): inhibits translation of mRNA
3.8.2.3 Gene Expression and Cancer
Benign vs malignant tumours
Tumour suppressor genes and oncogenes
Abnormal methylation of tumour suppressor genes and oncogenes
Increased oestrogen concentrations → some breast cancers
3.8.3 Using Genome Projects
Genome sequencing of many organisms including humans
Simpler organisms: genome → proteome (e.g. identifying potential antigens for vaccines)
Complex organisms: non-coding DNA and regulatory genes complicate genome → proteome translation
Sequencing methods continuously updated and automated
3.8.4 Gene Technologies
3.8.4.1 Recombinant DNA Technology
Transfer of DNA fragments between organisms/species; universal genetic code enables translation
Producing DNA fragments:
Reverse transcriptase: mRNA → cDNA
Restriction enzymes cut desired gene from DNA
Gene machine creates gene synthetically
Amplifying DNA fragments:
PCR (in vitro): polymerase chain reaction
Culture of transformed host cells (in vivo)
Insertion into vectors:
Addition of promoter and terminator regions
Restriction endonucleases and ligases insert fragments into vectors
Transformation of host cells
Marker genes detect GM cells/organisms
3.8.4.2 DNA Probes and Diagnosis
Labelled DNA probes and DNA hybridisation to locate specific alleles
Screening patients for heritable conditions, drug responses, health risks
Genetic counselling and personalised medicine
3.8.4.3 Genetic Fingerprinting
Genome contains many VNTRs (variable number tandem repeats)
Probability of two individuals having same VNTRs is very low
Technique: PCR amplification → analysis of DNA fragments
Applications: forensic science, medical diagnosis, animal/plant breeding
